==============================================================================
 ImmiJournal - Performance & Architecture Improvement Suggestions
 Generated: 2026-05-09
==============================================================================

1. DATABASE OPTIMIZATIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

1.1 Batch Tag Upserts (backend/routes/journal.py:33)
    Problem: `_sync_tags()` issues one INSERT per tag. For entries with many
    tags, this means N round-trips to SQLite.
    Suggestion: Use a single batched INSERT with `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`
    followed by a single SELECT to retrieve all IDs. Example pattern:

        INSERT INTO tags (name) VALUES (?), (?), (?)
        ON CONFLICT (name) DO NOTHING;
        SELECT id, name FROM tags WHERE name IN (?, ?, ?);

1.2 Stats GROUP BY Optimization (backend/routes/settings.py stats endpoint)
    Problem: `GROUP BY substr(created_at, 1, 7)` and `GROUP BY substr(created_at, 1, 10)`
    cannot use the `idx_entries_created_at` index since SQLite can't use
    indexes on expression-based groupings. With thousands of entries, this
    does a full table scan.
    Suggestion: Add computed columns `month_key TEXT GENERATED ALWAYS AS
    (substr(created_at, 1, 7))` and `day_key TEXT GENERATED ALWAYS AS
    (substr(created_at, 1, 10))`, then create indexes on those columns.
    Alternatively, create a materialized view/aggregate table updated on each
    entry insert that precomputes monthly/daily counts.

1.3 Linked Asset IDs Endpoint (backend/routes/journal.py `get_linked_asset_ids`)
    Problem: Returns ALL linked asset IDs without pagination. As the journal
    grows, this response payload grows unbounded.
    Suggestion: Accept an optional asset ID list from the frontend for bulk
    checking instead, or add pagination with `limit`/`offset` parameters.

1.4 Password Hashing (backend/auth.py)
    Problem: SHA-256 is used for password hashing. While this is a
    single-user local app, SHA-256 is fast and vulnerable to brute force.
    Suggestion: Upgrade to bcrypt (via `passlib` or `bcrypt` library) or
    Python's built-in `hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac`. This is a one-line change that
    significantly improves credential security.

2. IMAGE PROXY / CACHE OPTIMIZATIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

2.1 Disk Cache Size Calculation (backend/routes/immich_proxy.py
    `get_cache_size_mb()`)
    Problem: On every health check with `full=true`, and on hourly cleanup,
    all cache files are iterated to compute total size. With thousands of
    cached images, this is O(n) and can block.
    Suggestion: Maintain a running total of cache size in memory (increment
    on file write, decrement on eviction) instead of re-scanning the
    directory each time. Use an in-memory dict to track file sizes per path.

2.2 Cache Eviction Strategy
    Problem: Cache cleanup on app startup deletes non-sidecar files older
    than 24 hours with a full directory scan. The hourly cleanup does the
    same.
    Suggestion: Instead of scanning the entire cache directory each hour,
    maintain a sorted structure (e.g., a heap or sorted list) of
    (access_time, path, size) in memory. Only evict when approaching the
    500MB limit, removing oldest-first.

2.3 Image Proxy Content-Type Detection
    Problem: `imghdr.what()` and `puremagic` are called on every proxy
    response to detect image type, but Immich already returns
    `Content-Type` headers.
    Suggestion: Trust Immich's Content-Type header first; only fall back to
    magic byte detection if the header is missing or `application/octet-stream`.

3. BACKEND API OPTIMIZATIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

3.1 Response Caching Headers
    Problem: All `/api/*` responses get `Cache-Control: no-store` via
    middleware (backend/main.py CACHING_RULES), even for endpoints like
    `/api/stats` and `/api/journal/linked-asset-ids` that change rarely.
    Suggestion: Allow specific endpoints to override the no-store policy.
    `/api/stats` could use `Cache-Control: public, max-age=300` (matching
    the 5-minute server cache). `/api/journal/linked-asset-ids` could use
    short-term caching with revalidation.

3.2 Search Performance (backend/routes/journal.py FTS5 search)
    Problem: FTS5 search on `journal_entries_fts` triggers a join back to
    `journal_entries` in the same query. Both tables are scanned.
    Suggestion: Verify the FTS5 content table is external content (not a
    copy) so the FTS index doesn't duplicate text. Consider adding an
    `ORDER BY rank` clause for relevance sorting (requires bm25 or rank).

3.3 Entry Export
    Problem: `export_entries()` builds a full JSON response with all entry
    text and asset IDs in memory. For large journals this could be expensive.
    Suggestion: Stream the export as a download using `StreamingResponse`,
    or add a `limit`/`offset` parameter.

4. FRONTEND OPTIMIZATIONS
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

4.1 JavaScript Minification
    Problem: All JS files (~12 modules) are served unminified. While impact
    is minimal on LAN, it adds unnecessary bytes.
    Suggestion: Add a lightweight build step using `esbuild` or `terser` to
    minify JS and CSS. This can be a Dockerfile build stage that doesn't
    require npm in production.

4.2 CSS Minification
    Problem: `frontend/css/style.css` is ~1990 lines served unminified.
    Suggestion: Same as above - run through a CSS minifier in a build step.

4.3 Lazy-Loaded View Modules
    Problem: All view modules (feed.js, browse.js, entry.js, stats.js,
    settings.js) are imported eagerly in app.js, so all code loads upfront.
    Suggestion: Use dynamic `import()` to load view modules only when the
    user navigates to that tab. Since ES modules are already used, this is
    straightforward:

        case 'journal': {
            const { render } = await import('./views/feed.js');
            render();
            break;
        }

4.4 Virtual Scrolling for Large Lists
    Problem: In feed.js, infinite scroll appends all loaded cards to the DOM
    without removing off-screen elements. With hundreds of entries, DOM
    nodes accumulate and degrade scroll performance.
    Suggestion: Implement a simple recycling pattern - remove renderings
    for cards scrolled far off-screen (e.g., beyond 3000px viewport
    margin), or cap the feed at a visible window + buffer.

4.5 Date Formatting Cache (frontend/js/components/photoGrid.js)
    Problem: `_dateCache` memoizes date formatting, which is good, but it
    uses a plain object with no eviction policy. Over many sessions/dates,
    it grows indefinitely.
    Suggestion: Use an LRU cache with a reasonable max size (e.g., 500
    entries) or clear the cache when navigating away from the browse view.

4.6 Confetti Animation (frontend/js/confetti.js)
    Problem: The confetti animation runs a requestAnimationFrame loop
    that draws ~120 particles to a canvas. After animation ends, the canvas
    is removed but the rAF loop may still run for a frame on 0 opacity.
    Suggestion: Add a `cancelAnimationFrame` call on completion to ensure
    the loop stops cleanly. Current code sets `opacity=0` but continues
    drawing for the remaining duration.

4.7 Immich Config Cache (frontend/js/api.js)
    Problem: `_immichConfigCache` is fetched once and never invalidated.
    If the Immich instance URL changes, stale data persists until page reload.
    Suggestion: Add a TTL or expose an invalidation mechanism tied to
    settings updates.

5. INFRASTRUCTURE / DEPLOYMENT
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

5.1 Google Fonts External Dependency
    Problem: `index.html` loads Lora font from Google Fonts CDN with a
    `preconnect`. If the CDN is unreachable or slow, it blocks text
    rendering (even with `font-display: swap`, there's a FOIT flash).
    Suggestion: Self-host the Lora font files (WOFF2) in the frontend/assets
    directory. This removes the external network dependency entirely.

5.2 No Reverse Proxy Layer
    Problem: FastAPI serves static files directly. For production behind
    a reverse proxy (traefik/nginx), static files could be served from the
    proxy and API calls passed through.
    Suggestion: Document a reverse proxy configuration that serves static
    files from the proxy cache, bypassing the Python process entirely.

5.3 Docker Healthcheck
    Problem: The Docker Compose file has no `healthcheck` defined. Docker
    has no way to know if the container is healthy without one.
    Suggestion: Add a Docker healthcheck using `/api/health`:

        healthcheck:
          test: ["CMD", "curl", "-f", "http://localhost:8000/api/health"]
          interval: 30s
          timeout: 5s
          retries: 3
          start_period: 10s

6. TESTING
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

6.1 No Frontend Tests
    Problem: Zero automated frontend tests exist. All testing is backend-only.
    Suggestion: Add at minimum:
      - Unit tests for API fetch wrappers (api.js) with a mock fetch
      - Integration tests for entry creation flow using Playwright or
        Puppeteer targeting the Docker Compose environment
      - Snapshot tests for rendered HTML in entry cards/photos

6.2 Single Database Test Fixture
    Problem: All tests share the same in-memory SQLite database via a
    session-scoped fixture. Test ordering matters (e.g., conftest.py line 48
    truncates entries in setup but relies on session state).
    Suggestion: Use function-scoped fixtures to reset the database between
    tests, or explicitly reset the database before each test to avoid test
    coupling.

